---
import Section from '../common/Section.astro';

const groups = [
  {
    heading: "God's Mercy Awaits You",
    items: [
      {
        title: 'Welcome Home',
        content: 'If you\'re reading this, know that God has been waiting for you with open arms. Like the father in the parable of the Prodigal Son, He doesn\'t count the days you\'ve been away — He rejoices that you\'re here now.\n\nPerhaps it\'s been months, years, or even decades since your last confession. Perhaps you\'ve carried guilt and shame so heavy that you wondered if you could ever return. The beautiful truth is this: there is no sin too great for God\'s mercy, and no absence too long for His welcome.\n\n"Come now, let us settle the matter," says the LORD. "Though your sins are like scarlet, they shall be as white as snow." — Isaiah 1:18',
      },
      {
        title: 'Feeling Unworthy?',
        content: 'Many people feel they need to "clean up" before approaching confession — as if they must be worthy of God\'s mercy first. But this misunderstands the very heart of the sacrament.\n\nConfession is not for the perfect; it\'s for the broken. It\'s not a reward for the righteous; it\'s medicine for the sick. Jesus Himself said, "It is not the healthy who need a doctor, but the sick. I have not come to call the righteous, but sinners."\n\nYou don\'t need to have your life together. You don\'t need to feel holy. You simply need to come as you are, with whatever mess you\'re carrying, and let God do the rest.',
      },
      {
        title: 'No Sin Is Too Great',
        content: 'Sometimes we convince ourselves that what we\'ve done is beyond forgiveness — that we\'ve crossed a line God won\'t reach past. This is never true.\n\nSt. Peter denied Christ three times. St. Paul persecuted Christians. St. Augustine lived a life of sin for years. St. Mary Magdalene was possessed by demons. Yet each became a beloved saint, transformed by the very mercy available to you today.\n\nThe Church teaches clearly: any sin, no matter how grave, can be forgiven through a sincere confession. The only unforgivable sin is the one we refuse to bring to God\'s mercy.\n\n"Where sin increased, grace abounded all the more." — Romans 5:20',
      },
    ],
  },
  {
    heading: 'Understanding the Sacrament',
    items: [
      {
        title: 'What Is Confession?',
        content: 'Confession — also called Reconciliation or Penance — is one of the seven sacraments instituted by Jesus Christ Himself. On Easter evening, the risen Christ breathed on His apostles and said: "Receive the Holy Spirit. Whose sins you forgive are forgiven them." — John 20:22-23\n\nIn this sacrament, we encounter not a human judge, but Christ the Divine Physician. Through the priest, who acts in the person of Christ, we receive actual absolution — the certain forgiveness of our sins.\n\nThink of it as coming home after a long journey — tired, dusty, perhaps wounded — and being embraced by a Father who never stopped loving you.',
      },
      {
        title: 'Why Confess to a Priest?',
        content: '"Why can\'t I just confess directly to God?" This is perhaps the most common question about confession.\n\nThe simple answer: because Jesus designed it this way. He gave His apostles — and through them, all priests — the authority to forgive sins in His name. When you confess to a priest, you\'re confessing to Christ Himself, who works through the priest.\n\nSpeaking our sins aloud to another person breaks the power of secrecy and shame. Hearing "I absolve you" from a human voice makes God\'s forgiveness tangible, real, and certain.',
      },
      {
        title: 'The Seal of Confession',
        content: 'Everything you confess is protected by the most absolute secrecy imaginable — the Seal of Confession. A priest cannot reveal what he hears in confession under any circumstances, to anyone, for any reason. Ever.\n\nThis seal is so sacred that throughout history, priests have chosen imprisonment and even death rather than break it. It cannot be compelled by any civil authority, any bishop, or even the Pope himself.\n\nYou can speak freely. Your confession will never leave that confessional.',
      },
      {
        title: 'How Often Should I Confess?',
        content: 'The Church requires confession at least once a year if you\'re aware of mortal sin. But this is a minimum, not an ideal.\n\nMany saints and spiritual guides recommend monthly confession, even if you\'ve only committed venial sins. Regular confession builds spiritual strength, increases self-knowledge, provides accountability, and offers the grace to overcome habitual sins.\n\nRemember: confession isn\'t punishment for sinning. It\'s medicine for healing. We don\'t go to the doctor only when we\'re dying; we go to stay healthy.',
      },
      {
        title: 'Is This App a Replacement for Confession?',
        content: 'No — this app is not a replacement for the Sacrament of Confession.\n\nMetanoia is a spiritual preparation tool designed to help you examine your conscience, organize your thoughts, and approach the confessional with greater peace and clarity. It is meant to assist you on your journey toward reconciliation — not replace the sacred encounter with Christ through the priest.\n\nUse this app to prepare well. Then bring your heart — and your list — to a priest. That is where healing truly happens.\n\n"Whose sins you forgive are forgiven them." — John 20:23',
      },
    ],
  },
  {
    heading: 'Preparing Your Heart',
    items: [
      {
        title: 'Examining Your Conscience',
        content: 'Before confession, take time to prayerfully review your life since your last confession. This isn\'t about creating a perfect list — it\'s about honestly looking at where you\'ve fallen short of God\'s love.\n\nMany find it helpful to use the Ten Commandments as a guide: Have I put anything before God? Have I kept Sunday holy? Have I honored my parents? Have I harmed others in anger? Have I been faithful and pure? Have I stolen or been dishonest? Have I lied or harbored jealousy?\n\nAsk the Holy Spirit to reveal what needs healing. He will guide you gently.',
      },
      {
        title: 'What Is Contrition?',
        content: 'Contrition is sorrow for sin — but the Church recognizes two kinds, and both lead to forgiveness.\n\nPerfect contrition springs from love of God. You\'re sorry because you\'ve offended Someone infinitely good and loving. Imperfect contrition springs from fear of punishment or the ugliness of sin. This is enough for a valid confession.\n\nDon\'t worry if your sorrow feels imperfect. The fact that you\'re seeking confession at all shows the Holy Spirit is at work in you. God meets us where we are.',
      },
      {
        title: 'What If I Keep Falling Into the Same Sin?',
        content: 'This is one of the most discouraging struggles in the spiritual life. You confess, you resolve to change, and then... you fall again. Does God even take your confessions seriously anymore?\n\nYes. Absolutely yes.\n\nWhat God asks is not perfection but sincere effort. A valid confession requires the genuine intention to avoid sin. It does not require certainty of success.\n\nThink of a child learning to walk. She falls constantly. Does her father scold her for falling? No — he helps her up, encourages her, celebrates each wobbly step. Our Father in heaven is even more patient.',
      },
      {
        title: 'Confessing Number and Kind',
        content: 'The Church asks us to confess mortal sins by their kind (what the sin was) and number (how many times). This isn\'t to make confession harder — it\'s because honest, complete confession brings complete healing.\n\nYou don\'t need to give unnecessary details or tell long stories. Simply name the sin clearly. For habitual sins, an estimate is fine: "about once a week" or "several times."\n\nGod knows your heart — He\'s not looking for accounting precision, but honesty.',
      },
    ],
  },
  {
    heading: 'In the Confessional',
    items: [
      {
        title: 'What Do I Say?',
        content: 'Don\'t be nervous about "doing it right." The priest will guide you.\n\n1. Begin with: "Bless me, Father, for I have sinned. It has been [time period] since my last confession."\n2. Confess your sins honestly.\n3. When finished: "For these and all my sins, I am truly sorry."\n4. Listen to the priest\'s counsel and your penance.\n5. Pray the Act of Contrition.\n6. Receive absolution — the words that set you free.\n\nIf you get confused, just say: "Father, I don\'t remember how to do this. Can you help me?" That\'s perfectly fine.',
      },
      {
        title: 'What If I Forget Some Sins?',
        content: 'This worry keeps many people from confession. Here\'s the truth that should bring you peace:\n\nSins that are genuinely forgotten are forgiven along with the sins you confess. God sees your heart. If you sincerely examined your conscience and confessed what you remembered, your confession is valid and complete.\n\nIf you remember something later, simply mention it in your next confession. There\'s no need for panic or anxiety.\n\nGod isn\'t trying to catch you on technicalities. He wants to heal you.',
      },
      {
        title: 'The Priest Won\'t Judge You',
        content: 'Perhaps you\'re afraid of what the priest will think. Will he be shocked? Disgusted?\n\nPriests hear confessions constantly. They\'ve heard things you can\'t imagine. Your sins, however terrible they feel to you, will not shock them. They\'re not there to judge you — they\'re there to be Christ\'s instrument of mercy.\n\nMany priests describe hearing confessions as one of the most beautiful parts of their ministry. They witness miracles of grace and feel privileged, not burdened.\n\nAnd remember: the priest is a sinner too. He goes to confession himself. He\'s not above you — he\'s walking beside you.',
      },
    ],
  },
  {
    heading: 'After Confession',
    items: [
      {
        title: 'Understanding Your Penance',
        content: 'After hearing your confession, the priest gives you a penance — usually prayers or an action to perform.\n\nPenance isn\'t punishment. It\'s medicine. It helps repair the damage sin causes in us and in the world. Sometimes penances seem "too light" for serious sins. This reflects the overwhelming generosity of God\'s mercy.\n\nDo your penance as soon as possible, ideally before leaving the church. Approach it not as a burden but as a gift.',
      },
      {
        title: 'The Gift of Absolution',
        content: 'When the priest says the words of absolution — "I absolve you from your sins in the name of the Father, and of the Son, and of the Holy Spirit" — something real happens. Your sins are actually, truly forgiven. Not symbolically. Not hoped for. Done.\n\nSome people feel immediate peace and joy. Others feel nothing in particular. Both experiences are normal. Feelings come and go; God\'s forgiveness doesn\'t depend on them.\n\nIf doubts creep in later — remember: yes, He did forgive you. The sacrament worked. Stand on that truth, not on your feelings.',
      },
      {
        title: 'Growing in Grace',
        content: 'Confession isn\'t the end of the journey — it\'s a fresh start.\n\nStay close to the Eucharist. Pray daily, even a few minutes. Avoid occasions of sin — the situations, people, or habits that lead you into temptation. Practice virtue actively: generosity, patience, kindness.\n\nReturn to confession regularly. Don\'t wait until you\'ve accumulated serious sins. Monthly confession keeps your soul healthy and your relationship with God vibrant.\n\n"Blessed is the one whose transgression is forgiven, whose sin is covered." — Psalm 32:1',
      },
      {
        title: 'Indulgences and Temporal Punishment',
        content: 'Even after sins are forgiven, there can be lingering effects — what we call "temporal punishment." Think of it like this: a forgiven wound still needs time to heal.\n\nIndulgences are the Church\'s way of helping with this healing. Through prayer, acts of charity, and other practices, we can reduce these lingering effects — for ourselves and even for souls in Purgatory.\n\nThis isn\'t complicated theology — it\'s simply the Church\'s motherly care, helping us become not just forgiven but truly healed, fully restored, ready for heaven.',
      },
    ],
  },
  {
    heading: 'Common Questions',
    items: [
      {
        title: 'What Are Mortal and Venial Sins?',
        content: 'The Church distinguishes between mortal and venial sins to help us understand our spiritual state.\n\nMortal sin is deadly serious. It requires three things: grave matter (something seriously wrong), full knowledge (you knew it was wrong), and full consent (you chose to do it anyway). Mortal sin breaks our relationship with God and must be confessed before receiving Communion.\n\nVenial sin is less serious but still harmful. It weakens our relationship with God without breaking it completely. Confessing venial sins is highly recommended.\n\nWhen in doubt, confess it. What matters most is bringing everything to God\'s mercy.',
      },
      {
        title: 'What About General Absolution?',
        content: '"General absolution" — where a priest absolves many people at once — is valid only in genuine emergencies: danger of death with no time for individual confessions, or situations where people would be deprived of grace for a long time.\n\nIf you\'ve received general absolution, you must still confess mortal sins individually in your next regular confession.\n\nThe Church insists on individual confession because it\'s personal — you\'re not just part of a crowd, but a beloved child returning to your Father.',
      },
      {
        title: 'Do I Need to Make Restitution?',
        content: 'If your sin caused harm to others — stolen goods, damaged reputation, broken trust — true repentance includes making things right when possible.\n\nGod forgives you in confession regardless. But justice and charity call us to repair what we\'ve broken. If you stole, return what was taken. If you lied about someone, correct the record.\n\nSometimes restitution is impossible. In such cases, do what you can: pray for the person, give to charity, perform acts of kindness. The priest can help you think through what\'s appropriate.',
      },
    ],
  },
];
---

<Section background="white" class="py-20 md:py-32">
  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
    <div class="text-center mb-16">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-3xl md:text-4xl lg:text-5xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-4">
        Catholic Confession:<br />
        <span class="text-purple-700 dark:text-purple-400">Your Questions, Answered</span>
      </h2>
      <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 max-w-2xl mx-auto">
        Everything you want to know about the Sacrament of Reconciliation — drawn from the teachings of the Church and the wisdom of the saints.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="space-y-10">
      {groups.map((group) => (
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-serif text-lg font-semibold text-purple-700 dark:text-purple-400 uppercase tracking-wide mb-4">
            {group.heading}
          </h3>
          <div class="space-y-3">
            {group.items.map((item) => (
              <details class="group bg-white dark:bg-[#1a1a24] rounded-xl border border-gray-100 dark:border-white/5 overflow-hidden">
                <summary class="flex items-center justify-between gap-4 p-5 cursor-pointer list-none">
                  <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white text-left">
                    {item.title}
                  </h4>
                  <span class="flex-shrink-0 w-5 h-5 text-purple-600 dark:text-purple-400 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180">
                    <svg fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                      <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" />
                    </svg>
                  </span>
                </summary>
                <div class="px-5 pb-5 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 leading-relaxed whitespace-pre-line">
                  {item.content}
                </div>
              </details>
            ))}
          </div>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  </div>
</Section>

<style>
  details summary::-webkit-details-marker {
    display: none;
  }
</style>
